{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493329"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:06:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:06:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1292"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1292"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.75,0.05,0.02,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1292"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72538"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1292"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1292"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58008"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3382"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"8753"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1365"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72538"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETwo days following an elective Endoscopic Retrograde Cholangiopancreatography (ERCP), sphincterotomy and stone extraction, a 55-year-old woman is reviewed after complaining of nausea and epigastric pain. Her symptoms started two hours earlier. A case note review shows that the procedure was prolonged due to difficulty with manipulation around the papillary orifice. The patient is feeling unwell and has a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 110/60mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, and temperature of 38.0C. Her abdomen is soft apart from some epigastric tenderness. There is no guarding or rebound tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perforation","Pancreatitis","Sepsis","Haemorrhage","Cholangitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENausea and epigastric pain after an ERCP are suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Epost-ERCP pancreatitis\u003C/strong\u003E. The recognised causes of acute pancreatitis can be remembered by the mnemonic \u0022\u003Cstrong\u003EI GET SMASHED\u003C/strong\u003E\u0022: \u003Cstrong\u003EI\u003C/strong\u003Ediopathic, \u003Cstrong\u003EG\u003C/strong\u003Eallstones, \u003Cstrong\u003EE\u003C/strong\u003Ethanol, \u003Cstrong\u003ET\u003C/strong\u003Erauma, \u003Cstrong\u003ES\u003C/strong\u003Ecorpion sting, \u003Cstrong\u003EM\u003C/strong\u003Eumps, \u003Cstrong\u003EA\u003C/strong\u003Eutoimmune, \u003Cstrong\u003ES\u003C/strong\u003Eteroids, \u003Cstrong\u003EH\u003C/strong\u003Eypercalcaemia/\u003Cstrong\u003EH\u003C/strong\u003Eypertriglyceridaemia, \u003Cstrong\u003EE\u003C/strong\u003ERCP, and \u003Cstrong\u003ED\u003C/strong\u003Erugs (eg, thiazides, valproic acid). Whilst the mnemonic may aid recall of all the possible causes of acute pancreatitis, in practical terms it is important to understand that about 80% cases are due to either gallstones or alcohol. This patient falls into the third most common category - she has had a recent ERCP procedure and is at high risk of developing pancreatitis. All the listed options are potential complications of ERCP. However, pancreatitis is the most common complication among them. In most instances, the pancreatitis is mild and settles within a day or two.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforation\u003C/strong\u003E would present with peritoneal signs (eg, guarding, rebound tenderness). This patient does not have these peritoneal signs to suggest perforation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESepsis\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E would present with haemodynamic instability (eg, hypotension, tachycardia) and peritoneal signs. This patient\u0027s blood pressure is normal and does not have peritoneal signs, hence ruling out these two possible complications of ERCP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholangitis\u003C/strong\u003E may present with Charcot triad (eg, high fever, right upper quadrant pain, and jaundice) or Reynolds pentad (eg, Charcot triad PLUS hypotension and altered mental status). This patient has epigastric pain (NOT right upper quadrant pain) and does not have jaundice.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Some 5% of patients will have an episode of pancreatitis after an ERCP."],"references":["Thaker A, Mosko J, Berzin T. Post-endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography pancreatitis. Gastroenterology Report. 2014;3(1):32-40. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25406464/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58008"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1292"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58008"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T22:55:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T22:55:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1292"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72538"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"p